The nature oi the book must next be described. The Bursar was the chief officer of the monastery, under the

Prior, having under him all the other officers (obediera- tiorc'i) of the house, each of whom exhibited to him

yearly, at Pentecost, an account of his receipts and

expensas in his peculiar office. To the sacrist, for instance, were appropriated certain tithes and revenues to defray the expenses incidental to the performance of divine service in the church, the purchase of robes, and the repairs oi the fabric. Every other department had its respective head, but all accounted to the Bursam* and, when their various yearly account rolls had been laid before him, and had been duly examined and audited, one large roll was yearly compiled, called the
